title: Incompatability in C# with NuGet packages OnnxRuntime.GPU and OnnxTransformer
body:
**Describe the bug**
I am trying to run an onnx model in C# on GPU. I found that if I install NuGet packages Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Gpu (0.5.0) and Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer (1.3.1) together, I get the following exception:

System.EntryPointNotFoundException: 'Unable to find an entry point named 'OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_CUDA' in DLL 'onnxruntime'.'

when I try to create a `SessionOption`:

`var option = SessionOptions.MakeSessionOptionWithCudaProvider(); `

I tried this on two separate computers and both had the same error.

If I only have Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Gpu installed, the one line of code works fine creating the `SessionOptions` object. But once I add in the Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer package, I get the exception above.

**Urgency**
This prevents us from using ML.NET in our application. I am using Transforms.ApplyOnnxModel to consume our model, so I need to be able to reference Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer. At the moment my model works on the CPU with Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime, but inference on CPU is way too slow to be of any use.

**System information**  (First computer / second computer when applicable)
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 7 professional / Windows 10 professional
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): NuGet packages
- ONNX Runtime version: v0.5.0 Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Gpu, v1.3.1 Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer
- Python version: 3.6.5 / 3.7.3 Anaconda distribution
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2019
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version: CUDA 10.0.130, cuDNN 7.3.0.29
- GPU model and memory: NVidia Quadro K620 / NVidia Quadro P2000

**To Reproduce**
1. Create new C# console app targeting .Net core 3.0. 
2. Use NuGet Package Manager to install Microsoft.ML, Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Gpu and Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer.
3. Add the following line to the main method.
`            var option = SessionOptions.MakeSessionOptionWithCudaProvider();`
4. Start debugging. => "System.EntryPointNotFoundException".

**Expected behavior**
Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Gpu and Microsoft.ML.OnnxTransformer should be able to function properly together.

**Screenshots**
![ml_onnx](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43101410/66233737-a5657380-e6b1-11e9-87e3-cc965bd9d686.png)

**Additional context**

title: Fix NCHWc Conv/Add fusion when Conv node doesn't have bias tensor
body:
**Description**: 
Running the resnetv2_50 model from the ONNX model zoo with NCHWc optimizations turned on will crash accessing a nullptr NodeArg. This change fixes the bug with this fusion.

**Motivation and Context**
The Conv/Add fusion works by appending one of the Add operands as the "sum" tensor for the other Add operand, which must be a NchwcConv node. The fusion extended the number of inputs for this node to 4, but I totally misunderstood how the optional bias tensor was to be handled. The slot for this optional node must be set to a NodeArg with an empty string and the argument count for that slot must be 1. Otherwise, the runtime crashes inside Graph::BuildConnections.

A test case for the "no bias" case has also been added.

title: Yolo v3 inference 100x slower than expected
python session.run() fallback to CPU/CUDA provider for EP failures.
body:
python api session.run() fallback mechanism.

Problem Statement: Execution Provider internal failures cause session.run() to fail. 
An execution provider's GetCapability() implementation is supposed to accurately return what subgraphs on an ONNX model the EP can execute. However, for 3rd party EP's, sometimes the response is not accurate, leading to Onnxruntime assigning a subgraph to an EP, but the EP fails during runtime.

To satisfy ORT's requirement to be able to execute all valid ONNX models, we introduce a fallback/retry mechanism for the session.Run() api, which is enabled by default.

If Run() fails due to internal EP failure, it will recreate a new session and retry using default execution providers ['CPUExecutionProvider'] or ['CUDAExecutionProvider, 'CPUExecutionProvider'] (if gpu capable)

For example, if session.run() is invoked and the subgraph is assigned to TensorrtExecutionProvider but fails during execution, the session will be recreated and retried using CUDAExecutionProvider.
Similarly, if NGRAPHExecutionProvider fails, a new session is recreated and the session.run() retried using CPUExecutionProvider.

The session is recreated at most once. The retry only happens when EPFail exception is thrown by session.Run(). Thus, other exceptions thrown by ORT will not trigger the retry. 
Once the session is recreated and set to default providers, subsequent run() invocations will use the default provider settings. (to prevent the same failure from happening again)

For this PR, NGRAPHExecution provider was updated to return the proper EPFail status code.
Other EP's will be updated in subsequent PRs.

title: Changed ConvBase into a class member variable
body:
Currently, all Conv-family classes inherit from both ConvBase
and OpKernel. Since what ConvBase provides is all about
processing convolution attributes, it's more natural to move it as
a class member variable.

This change renamed ConvBase to ConvAttributes and moved
it into a separate file conv_attributes by its own. Instead of
inheriting from ConvBase, now each Conv-related class has a
class member variable that is of type ConvAttributes.

Hence, we removed necessary multiple inheritance and increase
composibility. More importantly, the change made it possible for
some other providers such as Nuphar be able to re-use the functionalities
provided by ConvAttributes class.

Note that we also made similar changes to ConvTransposeBase.
